body:
Hi React Team!

Right now the following code fails:

```
var spec = Object.create(null);
spec.render = function () {
  return <div />;
};
React.createClass(spec);
```

It fails because the function `mixSpecIntoComponent` called from `React.createClass` references `spec.hasOwnProperty`. But `spec` was created from `Object.create(null)`, so it doesn't have regular prototype methods like `hasOwnProperty`.

Here's a [patch](https://github.com/ryankaplan/react/commit/547af13f1fdc4772f9573e8ec19994691240f8c3) that fixes the issue. Let me know, based on my explanation below, if you agree that this is worth fixing and I can submit a PR.

---

Motivation for fixing this: I'm experimenting with building React bindings for a language called [Skew](http://skew-lang.org/). Skew compiles to Javascript (among other languages) and the map-type in Skew compiles to instances of `Object.create(null)`. That is: the Skew code `var map = { "hi": "there" }` translates roughly to `var map = Object.create(null); map["hi"] = "there";`. This is sensible - there's no need for a map to inherit from `Object.prototype`.

In Skew I'd like to be able to do something like...

```
React.createClass({
    "render": () React.Element => {
        return SkewReact.createElement("div");
    } 
})
```

Where `React.createClass` is the regular `createClass` function defined in the React library. But this fails because it passes a Skew map (which is `Object.create(null)` in Javascript)  to `createClass`. Instead I have to do something like:

```
SkewReact.createClass({
    ...
})
```

Where `SkewReact` will wrap the input into something that inherits `Object` before passing that on to the real `React.createClass`. This works, but means that my API won't mirror that of React directly which means it'll be harder for people to learn.
